"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "426.639","u": "Exactly the same city. We went back to Andrych&#195;w."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "430.266","u": "You returned to Andrych&#195;w. And what did your father do then?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "435.730","u": "He worked on the street with a shovel. Because the Germans demanded it. All men had to work on the street and the Jewish girls were taken to scrub floors and to wash windows."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "451.555","u": "For whom?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "452.941","u": "For the Germans. For the police. For everybody. And I was taken, but I worked well and worked very hard, because I intended to go to the Lieutenant and to tell him that I don&#39;t want to work for nothing and that I should get paid. And the other people worked without pay. And so it became possible for me to get three marks a day and that helped me a great deal, because I had to eat. And my father also earned something, and a few other Jews also worked well."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "490.269","u": "Did you have any money hidden?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "493.010","u": "No. We really didn&#39;t have such luck. We couldn&#39;t hide away anything. We had a family of five children, five not yet grown up children who couldn&#39;t earn their money, so everything was on the shoulders of the parents."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "510.619","u": "You told me before that you had horses and wagons. Did you return with those horses and wagons?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "518.372","u": "Yes, with one horse. The other horse was shot."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "522.468","u": "Who shot the horse?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "524.155","u": "He was hit by a piece of shrapnel."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "527.709","u": "Shrapnel! How did shrapnel happen to strike there?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "531.354","u": "Because we were returning together with the Polish Army on the same road, and many other carriages and lots of people have joined it. That was a terrible thing."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "547.209","u": "Why?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "548.264","u": "Because we were betrayed. It was known that the Polish Army was with us, and so they were shooting at us and we were in constant fear. We could not move to get anything for ourselves."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "566.107","u": "Now, and then what happened?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "569.963","u": "Then I remained two years at home, and in 1940 came the first blow. With the first transport they deported my brother who was at the time seventeen years old. It was terrible. And my father didn&#39;t want him to go alone to the lager. So he represented himself to be a man of fifty-six. It did not help that Mutti pleaded with him and I pleaded with him that he shouldn&#39;t leave us because it would be much more difficult for us without him. But he replied that he could not let the child go to the lager alone. He must go with him. And so he was accepted very readily. The Germans accepted him. And my father departed with my brother. In 1940. And then it became very hard for us. I had to work; the twelve year old child did work with a shovel in the street. We had to pay our rent, buy food and buy provisions to send packages to the lager."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "635.994","u": "Did they permit you to send packages?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "637.602","u": "Yes, we could send packages of two kilos."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "640.614","u": "How far away was the camp?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "642.783","u": "It was very far away. My father was with my brother in various camps. The first lager was Wischau. That is in Germany. I don&#39;t know where. Then he was in Flessing. That is near Gleiwitz. Then he was in Blechame near Sakrow. The last lager was Dachau."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "660.404","u": "The last lager was Dachau?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "661.621","u": "Yes. After a year my brother returned home. He was freed because he had a terrible leg. He did something to himself on purpose, so that he should be sent home."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "676.513","u": "By the Germans?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "677.278","u": "Yes, by the Germans. And the papa remained there. So since that time we don&#39;t know a thing . . . And we remained home for another year. In 1941 the whole city was evacuated. It was two weeks after my brother returned from the lager. He came from the lager and Mutti worked in another city in order to get a special card so that she would not be sent away. She worked there. And we three children, my brothers and I, were in the city, working on the street. And it was on the 10th of June in the year &#39;41 that the whole city was called to a big square."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "725.768","u": "Only the Jews?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "726.943","u": "Only the Jews. Naturally. And we were to be deported."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "732.467","u": "And what was the name of this city?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "735.238","u": "Andrych&#195;w."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "736.925","u": "That was in what district?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "739.527","u": "That was in the district of Bielitz. I was born in Wadowice but we lived in Andrych&#195;w. That wasn&#39;t far."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "751.425","u": "The whole city was called together? Where was your mother at that time?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "754.497","u": "My mother was in the other city where she worked. That was twelve kilometers away."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "759.377","u": "Oh. That was twelve kilometers away."},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "760.504","u": "Yes. And she had left in the evening because she worked on the night shift and she was to return by six o&#39;clock. We were deported Monday night. We saw our mother off at the station and we kissed her and she gave us instructions as to what we should do the next morning and, alas, we didn&#39;t know that we were seeing Mutti for the last time. And the next morning at six we got up to go to work. It was a wonderful day and there was nothing in the air at all . . . We didn&#39;t think at all that such a horrible thing may come. And here there come two Jewish policemen and two SS and tell us we were to go immediately to the square of assembly."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "811.403","u": "You told them that your mother was in the other city?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "814.066","u": "Indeed I told them. I was so dumb. I couldn&#39;t believe that the Germans could be so mean as to laugh at me. And I told them I have to wait for my mutti because she was supposed to return by six o&#39;clock. So they told me not to worry about Mutti, that Mutti will come, and so we had to go to the assembly square and there frightful things occurred before us. This I won&#39;t ever forget."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "841.953","u": "What happened there?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "843.339","u": "They took not only the healthy persons, but also the very old people who were almost unable to move, who were very sick. I myself, I personally saw a seventy-year-old woman, all swollen from sickness, being dragged along the grass because it was revulsive to them to lift her. She was all soft, from her swellings. But I could not look on. I was permitted to lift up that woman and to carry her on a bed to the big hall. And we saw various things that I could not forget. People were separated . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "887.611","u": "Tell me what happened to you. You were with your brother?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "893.225","u": "With two brothers. One who had returned from the lager."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "896.870","u": "And where is he now, the one who returned from the lager?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "899.159","u": "He isn&#39;t alive anymore."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "901.057","u": "He doesn&#39;t live anymore?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "902.033","u": "That is the one who just before liberation was sent to transport."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "906.172","u": "Oh, the one from the transport. Do you mean to say he returned and then he was sent away again?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "911.636","u": "No, but that is how we came to the square for assembly."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "914.979","u": "That means you and your two brothers."},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "918.142","u": "And we stood before a committee and they questioned us; we showed our work cards and they saw that we were three young and healthy people, so it was ordered that all three should be sent to the lager. This business was settled and I don&#39;t want to describe the whole scene."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "938.124","u": "I want you to tell me everything. Tell me what happened."},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "943.407","u": "My uncle stood there with three children."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "946.630","u": "Tell me only that which you have seen yourself. Your uncle stood there because"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "950.907","u": "Because all the people were distributed in groups. People for the camps, old people for transport to Auschwitz, and some people who were to remain in the same city for work. So there were three groups. What we saw made one&#39;s heart ache terribly. Just to see how these people treated us, that on one motion, on one gesture of a German man depended the fate and life of a person. If he made with the hand so, or so, [she demonstrates] that meant he would go for deportation from which nobody returned. My uncle with the three children stood on the side for deportation, while his wife with my mutti were working together. And he cried terribly and the children around him held on to his arms and they all cried terribly, and they yelled to me that I should transmit regards to his wife, and he didn&#39;t know that I too was being sent to a lager. He thought I will see his wife and he pleaded with me that I should console her, that he will return, that he will protect the three children and nothing will happen to them. And we saw his face and the little children and I will never forget it. There stood next to him a man whom I also knew very well. He was an acquaintance from our city who stood there with nine children. The oldest child was eleven years old. His wife also remained in the same city where my mutti worked; most of the women remained there."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1059.107","u": "What was there?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "1060.926","u": "A factory. A shop they called it. [It is interesting to note that the Germans used the English words shop]. They were sewing there for the Germans. Uniforms or sacks for bread for the soldiers. He stood there with his nine children. It was really . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1073.999","u": "How many children?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "1074.945","u": "Nine."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1076.252","u": "Your uncle with nine children?"},    {"who": "Fela Nichthauser", "start": "1077.758","u": "No, that man with the nine children. The oldest was eleven years old. And indeed when one saw it, how one&#39;s heart could be moved, and all the nine children started crying and their faces looked horrible. Really, I don&#39;t find words."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1098.391","u": "And so your uncle with his thr